description.text:
A simple cupholder for vehicles without factory cupholders, but with a cassette deck head unit.

Requires the car stereo to be in "ejected" mode, so you can't have coffee and listen to cassettes at the same time!

Works for small (12oz) and medium (16oz) UK size cups.

Only tested in a W202 Mercedes, so test your own setup is secure before using and use for hot liquids at your own risk

Placing liquids in some cars can risk damage to electronic parts - e.g. the W210 Mercedes where the (factory) cupholder can spill and break the gearbox controller.

I have included two angles - 0 and 25 degrees. The W202 needs the 25 degree incline to keep the coffee upright. Feel free to customise, or heat and bend.

Have fun.

title: TEVO BlackWidow - Control Box for custom hardware
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
Custom Control Box for TEVO Black Widow

I wanted to get rid of the too-big control box delivered by TEVO for its BlackWidow 3DPrinter. The idea was to mount a control box directly on the vertical C-BEAM.
Stock MKS-GEN and 12864 LCD display were also too big for that project. Fortunately, MKS designed light versions of these devices ... direct in the shopping cart and ordered

This control box needs the following devices :

  • MKS GEN-L (ordered from Makerbase shop on AliExpress)
  • LCD MKS MINI12864LCD (ordered from Makerbase shop on AliExpress)
  • C14 Connector (got from stock printer)
  • 16mm latching switch (got from stock printer)
  • TEVO (or other brands) MOFSET (to manage Heating Bed)
  • 2x 4010 24V fans (on mine I used 12V fans with an additional '24V to 12V' converter)

Options :

  • 19mm latching switch (to manage LED strips)
  • 25A SSR 220V Solid State Relay (if you want to use a 220V silicone heater)

Notes:

Supports are only needed for the big square holes, ie :

  • the hole for the display LCD screen
  • the holes for the 4010 fans
  • the hole for the USB hole (but not necessary)

This has been done in FreeCAD, and the file is fully parametric. All the dimensions can be adjusted, but that is not as straightforward as with well documented OpenSCAD models. Ask if you need help with that. FreeCAD should be easy for users of SolidWorks etc., for others, look for some video tutorials at http://sourceforge.net/apps/mediawiki/free-cad/index.php?title=Main_Page or youtube. And I recommend using the latest bleeding edge "daily" release, they seem stable enough and new features appear often.

title: Rear Mount Z-Axis Support Brace for Wanhao Duplicator i3
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
There’s lots of Z-axis support designs for the Wanhao i3/Monoprice Maker Select on Thingiverse, but I much prefer the ones mounted at the back, like https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2391089 and https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2476118. They keep the print bed nice and accessible from the front.

I also like the minimalist design of the RepRap Champion Z-brace, but didn’t like its front-mount and how much it would cost to import it to where I live (the UK). So I came up with my own design :)

My comfort zone is still old-school steel, wood, nuts and bolts – so there’s nothing 3D printed in this design. But that also makes it reasonably quick and easy to build. Yes you could 3D print the brackets in some hours, but why bother when you can buy stronger ones for cheap on eBay or at your local shop? (Am I going to get kicked off Thingiverse for saying that? :) )

Materials List

You might want to remind yourself how a turnbuckle and regular right-hand vs. atypical left-hand threads work before reading further…

  • 2 – Right hand male rod ends 5mm bore (M5) – e.g. these which say they are equivalent to GAKFR5PB, SAKAC5M SM5, MB-M05
  • 2 – Left hand male rod ends 5mm bore (M5) – e.g. these which say they are equivalent to SALKAC5M, MBL-M05
    -- Note “rod ends” may also be called “rod end bearings,” “heim joints” (North America) or “rose joints” (UK and elsewhere) when you’re shopping
  • 4 – 8mm i/d x 40mm nylon rawl wall plugs – e.g. these
    -- I could not find the right-hand and left-hand threaded counter nuts – a.k.a. “insert nuts” or “threaded inserts” or “rivnuts” that I really wanted, so the wall plugs were my 3rd or 4th choice
  • 6 – M5 x 15mm socket cap head machine bolts
  • 4 – M5 nuts
  • 2 – M5 washers
  • 4 – M3 x 8mm socket cap head machine bolts (slightly longer than the M3s they’re replacing on the Z frame)
  • 4 – M3 washers
  • 2 – 76mm (3-inch) L-shaped metal corner brackets
    -- You’ll most likely need to drill 2 M3 holes in each L-bracket, to match the existing holes on the top sides of the printer’s Z frame. Use a pencil through the Z frame holes to mark the perfect spots on your brackets
  • 2 – 50mm corner brace angle brackets (I did have to trim 1 of these to not overlap the i3 Pro’s power switch)
    -- Invest in “heavy duty” (i.e. not cheap junky) angle and L-brackets, as you don’t want them bending when they’re supposed to be holding your Z axis rock-solid
  • Black spray paint (to pretty-up those brackets so they match the printer)
  • 2 – aluminium round tubes – 12.7mm (1/2-inch) OD x 16swg (or so) – I cut mine to 340mm long each, but mount your 4 brackets and 4 rod ends first, and then you’ll see how long the tubes need to be…

Leave enough rod end thread exposed (at both ends of the tubes) so you can turn the tubes turnbuckle-style to adjust your printer’s Z-axis. Your Z frame should already be reasonably true before mounting this brace… which is just for the last fine Z adjustments and stability during prints.

Once you have all the parts (researching “what fits with what” took 90% of this project’s time for me) it’s an easy build. Hopefully the photos tell it all.

The brackets above are long enough to keep the tubes clear of the X-axis gantry, stepper motors, etc. on a Wanhao i3 Plus. The original “non-Plus” models have more wires and stuff sticking out the back of that gantry – you may need to give them more room with longer brackets (?)… if so make sure they are sturdy brackets because that’s even more leverage exerted on them.

Das Bienenwabenlampensystem besteht aus mehreren druckbaren Komponenten:

Wabensegment zum bestücken mit 10 mm breiten LED-Band und aufschnappen auf Grundhalter (Beispiellampe: 9)
Grundhalter Segment 1 mit einem Führungsquader (Beispiellampe: 4)
Grundhalter Segment 2 mit zwei Führungsquadern (Beispiellampe: 3)
Abdeckkappe 1 Zungen (Beispiellampe: 9)
Abdeckkappe 2 Quader (Beispiellampe: 10*)

Der Grundhalter wird mittels Führungsnuten und entsprechenden Nasen zusammengesteckt und mit Kleber (ich verwende in Aceton aufgelöstes ABS) fixiert.
Die Grundform kann (fast) beliebig variieren. Die Grundhalter können entweder an der langen oder an der schmalen Seite zusammengeklickt werden. Hier im Beispiel hat sie die Form eines Kreuzes.
Grundhalter Segment 1 und Segment 2 wechseln sich immer ab.
Anschließend werden die benötigten Wabensegmente (im Beispiel 9 Stück) mit dem LED-Lichtband bestückt. Das Band wird nur zwischen die beiden Führungsschienen gedrückt und nicht verklebt. Dabei können die LEDs nach außen oder nach innen gerichtet werden (siehe Bild). Im Beispiel sind die beiden innersten nach innen gerichtet und alle anderen nach außen. Die Lichtausbeute ist bei nach außen gerichteten LEDs höher! Das LED-Band wird mittels Schere an den „erlaubten“ Stellen entsprechend gekürzt und z.B. mit einer Zwillingslitze verbunden. Als Querschnitt sollten mind. 0,2 mm2, bei größeren Lampen mehr verwendet werden. Im Beispiel wurde ein Flachbandkabel mit 4 Litzen (zusammengeschlossen: je zwei für Plus und Minus 12V) verwendet.
Als LED-Band wird im Beispiel folgender Typ benutzt: V-TAC "SMD 5730" mit 20-22 Lumen pro Chip, damit ergibt sich pro 4er-Segment ca. 900 Lumen und die Lampe hat insgesamt ca. 8000 lm. Davon muss natürlich abgezogen werden, was durch die schlechte Transparenz des ABS verloren geht und ebenso nach innen gerichtete LED-Elemente. Die Lampe ist trotzdem sehr hell und kann z.B. locker eine einzelne 58 Watt Leuchtstoffröhre ersetzen. Die Lichtfarbe des verwendeten LED-Bandes ist sehr warm und ähnelt früheren Glühlampen.
Die Halter wurden mittels weißem ABS und die Wabensegmente mit „naturfarbenem“ ABS gedruckt.
Beim zusammenklicken ist zu beachten, daß die Schnappzungen richtig einschnappen - evtl. ist das Wabensegment um 90 Grad zu drehen!
Die Abdeckkappen werden farbig nach Wahl gedruckt (hier grün) und müssen, bei Schwergängigkeit etwas nachgearbeitet oder, falls sie nicht halten, mittels Kleber (Klebestift) befestigt werden.
Als Steuergerät wird z.B. folgender Typ verwendet: LPV-60-12
Bei größeren Lampen muss die Stromversorgung von beiden Seiten des LED-Leuchtbandes erfolgen!
Ich habe das Steuergerät auf einem Regal in der Nähe der Lampe befestigt und nur die 12V Versorgung zu der Lampe installiert (hier Zwillingslitze mit 2*0,75 mm2).

----------------------------------------- english -----------------------------------------------------------------

The honeycomb lamp system consists of several printable components:

Honeycomb segment to equip with 10 mm wide LED strip and snap onto base holder (example lamp: 9)
Basic holder segment 1 with a guide block (example lamp: 4)
Basic holder segment 2 with two guide blocks (example lamp: 3)
Cover 1 tabs (example lamp: 9)
Cover 2 cuboid (example lamp: 10*)

The basic holder is put together by means of guide grooves and corresponding noses and fixed with adhesive (I use ABS dissolved in acetone).
The basic form can vary (almost) arbitrarily. The basic holders can be clicked together either on the long side or on the short side. Here in the example it has the shape of a cross.
Basic holder segment 1 and segment 2 always alternate.
Then the required honeycomb segments (in the example 9 pieces) are equipped with the LED light band. The tape is only pressed between the two guide rails and not glued. The LEDs can be directed outwards or inwards (see picture). In the example, the two innermost ones are directed inwards and all others are directed outwards. The light output is higher with LEDs facing outwards! The LED tape is shortened accordingly by means of scissors at the "allowed" positions and e.g. connected to a twin strand. As a cross-section, at least 0.2 mm2 should be used, for larger lamps more. In the example, a ribbon cable with 4 strands (together: two each for plus and minus 12V) was used.
As an LED strip, the following type is used in the example: V-TAC "SMD 5730" with 20-22 lumens per chip, resulting in per 4-segment about 900 lumens and the lamp has a total of about 8000 lm. Of course, this must be deducted, which is lost due to the poor transparency of the ABS and also inward-looking LED elements. The lamp is still very bright and can e.g. Loosely replace a single 58 watt fluorescent tube. The light color of the LED strip used is very warm and resembles earlier incandescent bulbs.
The holders were printed using white ABS and the honeycomb segments with "natural" ABS.
When clicking together, make sure that the snap tabs snaps in correctly - possibly the honeycomb segment must be turned 90 degrees!
The cover caps are printed in color of your choice (here green) and have to be slightly reworked if they are stiff or, if they do not hold, they have to be fixed with glue (glue stick).
As a power supply, e.g. the following type is used: LPV-60-12
For larger lamps, the power must be connected from both sides of the LED strip!
I have mounted the controller on a shelf near the lamp and installed only the 12V supply to the lamp (here twin wire with 2 * 0.75 mm2).

description.text: Made in Fusion360.

We are a student team from different disciplines of the RWTH Aachen University and have created this project in the context of the 2017 iGEM competition.

After all the work that went into our pump, we would like to share our results with you!

We built this peristaltic pump as generally applicable liquid handling solution for any project which requires transportation of liquids. Our pump is capable of precise dosing and pumping, providing a wide range of dosing volumes and flow rates to maximize possible applications. Through 125 dosing experiments we were able to demonstrate and quantify the accuracy of our pump. For a tubing with 0,8 mm inner diameter and any flowrate or dosing volume within the specifications we could show an accuracy better than 2% deviation from the set value. Given the results of the measurements, the accuracy can be improved even further if the speed of the calibration is adjusted to the required flow rate.

The pump can be controlled without programming knowledge via the built-in LCD display and a rotary knob. In addition, the pump can be remotely controlled via USB by serial commands. This simple way of communication is compatible with common software and programming languages (MATLAB, LabVIEW, Java, Python, C#, etc.).

The pump is simple and inexpensive to manufacture, with all the parts totaling less than $100 compared to $1300 for the cheapest comparable commercial solution we could find. Besides a 3D printer, only common tools are needed. Our project is open source in terms of hardware and software. We provide the CAD files for the 3D printed parts, a complete list of all required commercial components and their sources, and the source code used in our pump.

Please visit our official wiki for further information:
http://2017.igem.org/Team:Aachen/Hardware

In addition to our wiki, we have also published a construction manual at instructables:
http://www.instructables.com/id/Open-Source-Peristaltic-Pump/

You can find the software for the Arduino at GitHub:
https://github.com/iGEM-Aachen/Open-Source-Peristaltic-Pump

The iGEM (international Genetically Engineered Machine) Foundation is an independent, non-profit organization dedicated to education and competition, the advancement of synthetic biology, and the development of an open community and collaboration.
iGEM runs three main programs: the iGEM Competition - an international competition for students interested in the field of synthetic biology; the Labs Program - a program for academic labs to use the same resources as the competition teams; and the Registry of Standard Biological Parts - a growing collection of genetic parts used for building biological devices and systems.

description.text:
First introduction

Printer: Tevo Tarantula, dual extruder, 2x E3Dv6 hotend and integrated layer fan

Problem: The printers frame limits x-travel

Solution: new x-axis, containing MGN12 linear rail upgrade. It keeps the frame and the size itself.

Dual-z-drive is recommended. maybe it's possible with only one lead screw, don't know.
There are options to put the motors on top or to the bottom.

you need 400mm linear rods and LM8UU bearings, the lead screw and threaded rod from the stock tarantula should work, it's same height so far.

easiest way: steppers at the bottom, the bracket takes the stepper and the rod, on top the corner bracket stabilizes the frame and has the opposite end of the rod, so it cannot move and everything is square.

if you want to have the motors on top you need to put something between the bottom end of the rods and the base. to guide the rod at the bottom and to prevent that it will fall out.
you can use the frame sockets on the left and the right and the small cylinders. as a guide you can use the bottom motor bracket without motor (or edit the source CAD and remove motor cutouts, make the piece smaller).

one of the pros of the solution with motors on top is the free space at the bottom. It's possible that the lead screw could hit the coupler before the nozzle touches the bed.
The coupler can be moved down more, but then there stays less space to tight the scrub screw against the threaded rod. You can shorten the motor shaft in worst case, lower the stepper is nearly impossible.
I'ts primary a problem with stock y-axis, not with a MGN12 guided bed.

x-axis

After replacing the early version with an enforced one that faces directly to the extrusion on two sides the x-axis is moving fine.
The pulley on the motor-side uses a M3x25 screw. If you have longer you can use a nut, else the opposite hole is designed to get self tapped. The idler side uses M5x35 screws and nuts. Insert a 0.75mm washer between the pulleys and the thin walls and the stock 5mm spacer plus washer on the other side to center the pulley to the extrusion so the belt runs straight.

If you go with z-axis motors on top and the setup in the 2nd image below, the challenge is a fixed point for the rod at the bottom. Most rods length is 300 or 400 or 500mm. the resulting distance needs to be negotiated with a pin at the bottom or by a attachment between the top z corner bracket and the rod.

Maybe you will use the frame sockets on the corners. these 2 are simple to complete with the other from www.thingiverse.com/thing:1458534
I used the same bottom height.

most easiest method is inverted z-axis with reasonable expenditure as I made it. It's including the bottom stand for the rod and needs a minimum of printed parts.

motors at the bottom motors on top , needs the sockets on the left and right motors on top with simple guides at the bottom. Sockets aren't required. motors on top, uses the sockets on the left and right with the extension on top and takes the 400mm rod exactly between these parts. remove or insert the different pieces of the socket, so you can configure it for your needs. not every combination is possible and not every combination makes sense. the light blue e.g. has a different fillet then the default. If you use the light blue with the pin above but don't configure the z-axis stepper motors to the bottom you can enforce the socket with the blue part above. The red one finishes the fillet to be continuous an all edges. call it modular. or call it confusing. depends on you :)

title: Modular Tree for Conan Boardgames and other dungeon crawlers

description.text:
These are models for tree obstacles in Monoith's Conan boardgames. The tree sections slide into a central clip that doubles as a platform to indicate whether models are in, under, or over a tree. The tree does not obscure the board art which is important for zone saturation rules.

I intend for the trees to be useful in other games. Some games prohibit moving into brush or tree zones, others give you conditions, others let you climb or fly over trees. These tree models should handle all of these cases clearly while still providing the scenery.

Additionally for games with LOS rules the trees can be set up to either interfere or to indicate when LOS crosses the tree without causing difficulties you have with more traditionally modeled trees in scatter terrain.

The trees are textured on one side and flat on the other for easy printing. If you are a painter you can probably print them half height and slide two sections into each clip resulting in two textured sides that should be easy to wash.

There is one optional clip for the top if having the tree sections uneven gives you skin crawlies.
